Perfect! Works very well with Linux Mint 18 and Bitwig 1.3.14 Brief rundown 
of the steps I use: 1. modprobe snd-aloop to create virtual midi devices 2. 
touchosc2midi as a bridge 3. QjackCtl to route audio/alsa/midi connections 
4. In Jack patchbay, connect Output RtMidiOut Client to Input Virtual Raw 
Midi 5. Make sure Bitwig is configured for Jack driver and TouchOSC 
controller is configured for virtual midi

i've been waiting for a custom layout update for a while and i'm rather thrilled to finally see it.  there's only one problem, really; the "local ip address" setting in the OSC parameters menu is read-only, so if it's wrong, you're out of luck.  apparently CM10 on my sensation lists the wlan interface at a low metric, so the only way i can get touchOSC to acknowledge my connected host/midi bridge is to turn on airplane mode and then reset my phone which is, honestly, incredibly inconvenient, especially since turning airplane mode off again puts the local ip address setting back to my mobile internet IP address.  if we could specify which interface touchosc looks for hosts from, it would be perfect.  right now, it's barely usable on my phone which isn't the app's fault, but it is really obnoxious.  [update about 19 months later]  well there's been absolutely no update nor mention beyond the response from the dev a year and a half ago and the app is still unusable because it defaults to mobile network IP instead of WLAN.  2 stars removed because it has worked if i reboot with mobile data turned off but that's an absurd workaround.

Ok, upping the stars to 3 from 1. I was about 20 minutes away from making it work but it took a lot of effort. The app is solid enough, so I take stars away because of the documentation and the clumsy install. But, once I made it work - it's pretty cool (5 stars for coolness hexler). I dunno, maybe I expecting too much for a $5 app....  Original review... updated above... As tantalizing as this app sounds, I cannot recommend it. You need to get the tablet communicating with the computer. I have an Android tablet and a Mac computer. The instructions are not available for this configuration, so you have to figure it out from the IOS devices. First, your Mac needs something called X11, which is not included in recent OSX installs. Need to find and install. Then install something called pd extended and figure out IP addresses. Then install TouchOSC bridge, then install TouchOSC editor, which won't work because I don't have java...   I don't see anything easy about "easily connect to any MIDI capable application". I've spent hours just to figure out the communication part. Save your money. I would request a refund from the play store, but 15 minutes is all they give you.
